'''Kansha Shrine''' (かんしゃじんじゃ) is a shrine {{ill|lt=enshrined|Q1793334|qid=Q1793334|1=Boca do Acre}} in Obata-chō, {{ill|lt=Ise|Q328067|qid=Q328067|1=Ise, Mie}}, {{ill|lt=Mie Prefecture|Q128196|qid=Q128196|1=Mie Prefecture}}. It is an {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Engishiki shrine|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286|lt=Shikinaisha}}, and its former shrine rank was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=prefectural shrine|1=Ken-sha|qid=Q90139226}}. Originally it was called “Miyake Jinja,” but now it is called “Kansha Jinja” or “Rikyū-san”<ref>{{Cite web|title=官舎神社|url=https://genbu.net/data/ise/kansya_title.htm|access-date=2025-12-2}}</ref>.

=== History ===
It began in {{ill|lt=Tenpyō-Shōhō|Q1373169|qid=Q1373169|1=Tenpyō-shōhō}} 8, when {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kasuga Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} in {{ill|lt=Nara|Q11444975|qid=Q11444975|1=Nara}} was invited and enshrined as the {{ill|lt=ancestral deity|Q85882782|qid=Q85882782|1=Oyagami}} of the {{ill|lt=Nakatomi clan|Q1198447|qid=Q1198447|1=Nakatomi clan}}<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mie Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines: Kansha Shrine|url=http://kyoka.mie-jinjacho.or.jp/shrine/%e5%ae%98%e8%88%8e%e7%a5%9e%e7%a4%be/|access-date=2025-12-2}}</ref>. After falling into ruin in the medieval period, it was revived in {{ill|lt=Kanbun|Q1146228|qid=Q1146228|1=Kanbun (era)}} 3<ref>{{Cite web|title=官舎神社|url=http://engishiki.org/ise/bun/is080151-01.html|access-date=2025-12-2}}</ref>. In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 12 it became a {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}. In Meiji 13, Obata Shrine (Yahashira Shrine) was merged. In {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 19, it was promoted to prefectural shrine<ref>{{Cite web|title=Mie Prefecture Association of Shinto Shrines|url=http://kyoka.mie-jinjacho.or.jp/shrine/%e5%ae%98%e8%88%8e%e7%a5%9e%e7%a4%be/|access-date=2025-12-27}}</ref>.

